    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0bb7aa349fa5f93a",
      "text": "# Comments from Agile Cambridge 2022"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9dcfba9cd297f8eb",
      "text": "What are the risks of chosen indicators? What behaviours do they shape? They can be treated as goals, not as measures that provide a holistic view of what is going on in order to inform and support decision-making.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "156c0d0be53161c0",
      "text": "Which metrics could be used? How to access if the chosen indicators are helpful or harmful? ODIM (outcome, decision, insight, measure) framework can help the choice. Value and business impact metrics can also be useful, they are lagging indicators that move a long time after the action has been taken.\n\nThere can also be external factors and emergent issues that influence the indicators.\n\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9b28503107ec44cd",
      "text": "How to prevent indicators to become managers' goals? There is a fundamental difference between using indicators to control people that cannot be trusted or because there is an oversimplified understanding of what is going on Vs using indicators to support decision-making and understanding the contextual value of indicators, their non-linearity, and the potential impact of external factors.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "03757b9980bddfa6",
      "text": "\"It is important to keep communications with client/wider organisation and show progress.\" There is a difference between traditional approaches which uses plan and metrics to demonstrate progress Vs the Agile approach which demonstrates progress by what is delivered and validated, in this case in the achievement of the improvements pursued.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4e44928c910bb52f",
      "text": "Do metrics need to be consistent across teams? Does everyone use the same indicators? Metrics and indicators are chosen to answer specific questions and not to compare teams, and so they change from time to time and from team to team based on the burning question that is faced."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e7b8ccb0fd16a390",
      "text": "# Comments from SPA 2021\n\nLike in a triage use a set of indicators to inform human judgment and not individual metrics that are also easier to game.\n\nIn the same way a doctor identifies a set of tests based on what she/he is investigating, a different set of indications may be fit for different circumstances.\n  \nBe aware of the potential influences of external factors and of unintended consequences.\n  \nConsider also asking the teams doing the work, they may already know the answer to your questions.\n  \nInspection of the indicators should not cause the work to stop or require tangible time and effort from anyone. They should be lightweight, automated, and access ready-available public data. Like having a continuous flow of real-time telemetry. Priority should be given to being non-intrusive and lightweight."
    }
